42
00:01:40,840 --> 00:01:43,760
Now what we're calling a
great books initiative at MIT

43
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:47,160
is, so far, a sequence
of two subjects,

44
00:01:47,160 --> 00:01:49,840
Classics of Western Philosophy
offered in the fall,

45
00:01:49,840 --> 00:01:52,940
and Ancient Authors offered
by literature in the spring.

46
00:01:52,940 --> 00:01:54,620
The courses are
loosely integrated.

47
00:01:54,620 --> 00:01:55,940
They have common themes.

48
00:01:55,940 --> 00:01:57,220
There's minimal overlap.

49
00:01:57,220 --> 00:01:59,160
So it would make
sense for a student

50
00:01:59,160 --> 00:02:01,120
to take both, which
we're going to encourage.

51
00:02:01,120 --> 00:02:05,502
They don't have a unified set
curriculum of great books.

52
00:02:05,502 --> 00:02:06,960
And in each case,
the subjects were

53
00:02:06,960 --> 00:02:10,080
ones we were really keen to
teach but unable to staff

54
00:02:10,080 --> 00:02:12,940
reliably without
donor-directed funds.

55
00:02:12,940 --> 00:02:14,760
So we have a three-year
pilot right now

56
00:02:14,760 --> 00:02:16,240
for which we're
extremely grateful,

57
00:02:16,240 --> 00:02:19,560
to race data and analog devices.

58
00:02:19,560 --> 00:02:23,500
So why were we excited
about teaching great books?

59
00:02:23,500 --> 00:02:26,280
And what does it mean
to talk in those terms?

60
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:28,800
There are grounds
for skepticism.

61
00:02:28,800 --> 00:02:32,000
So great books, courses,
programs and colleges are

62
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,740
an artifact of the first
half of the 20th century,

63
00:02:34,740 --> 00:02:37,480
beginning with John Erskine's
General Honors at Columbia

64
00:02:37,480 --> 00:02:38,580
in 1920.

65
00:02:38,580 --> 00:02:43,000
It was discontinued in 1928,
but then revived and revamped

66
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,960
as Literature
Humanities in 1937.

67
00:02:45,960 --> 00:02:48,680
Meanwhile, Columbia
defector Mortimer Adler

68
00:02:48,680 --> 00:02:51,660
left for Chicago in 1930.

69
00:02:51,660 --> 00:02:54,480
And that took up the mantle
of great books education.

70
00:02:54,480 --> 00:02:58,320
And then another landmark was
St. John's College Indianapolis

71
00:02:58,320 --> 00:03:00,440
was the first college
devoted to a great books

72
00:03:00,440 --> 00:03:03,080
curriculum in 1937.

73
00:03:03,080 --> 00:03:06,480
If you flash forward to the
present, programs like these

74
00:03:06,480 --> 00:03:09,200
are notable for their
relative absence.

75
00:03:09,200 --> 00:03:10,720
And they've come
to be associated

76
00:03:10,720 --> 00:03:13,720
with political
conservatism, and those

77
00:03:13,720 --> 00:03:17,920
who advocate for great books
with a reactionary narrative

78
00:03:17,920 --> 00:03:20,380
that has three parts that
I want to talk about.

79
00:03:20,380 --> 00:03:23,360
So one is an idea that
the Western canon reflects

80
00:03:23,360 --> 00:03:26,520
the key ideas,
democracy, liberalism,

81
00:03:26,520 --> 00:03:28,720
maybe the scientific
method of something

82
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:30,920
called Western civilization.

83
00:03:30,920 --> 00:03:35,140
The second idea is that
academics enamored of feminism,

84
00:03:35,140 --> 00:03:38,760
post-colonialism, and
multiculturalism dismantled this

85
00:03:38,760 --> 00:03:41,820
canon in the 1980s and 1990s.

86
00:03:41,820 --> 00:03:44,720
And the third idea is that
the predictable result of this

87
00:03:44,720 --> 00:03:48,200
was the decline of the
humanities, which had betrayed

88
00:03:48,200 --> 00:03:50,680
their cultural inheritance.

89
00:03:50,680 --> 00:03:54,612
Now every element of that
narrative is misleading.

90
00:03:54,612 --> 00:03:56,820
In an essay on
Western civilization--

91
00:03:56,820 --> 00:03:59,300
I encourage you to read it,
published in The Guardian--

92
00:03:59,300 --> 00:04:03,800
Kwame Anthony Appiah argues that
there's really no such thing.

93
00:04:03,800 --> 00:04:06,260
Now he begins with a
probably apocryphal anecdote.

94
00:04:06,260 --> 00:04:07,740
But I'm going to
repeat it anyway,

95
00:04:07,740 --> 00:04:09,698
which is that when he
was asked what he thought

96
00:04:09,698 --> 00:04:13,560
of Western civilization, Mahatma
Gandhi is said to have replied,

97
00:04:13,560 --> 00:04:17,440
I think it will be
a very good idea.

98
00:04:17,440 --> 00:04:20,320
But where Gandhi implies
that the West was never

99
00:04:20,320 --> 00:04:24,080
truly civilized, Appiah
goes one step further,

100
00:04:24,080 --> 00:04:27,680
suggests that Western
civilization is a bad idea

101
00:04:27,680 --> 00:04:28,840
intellectually.

102
00:04:28,840 --> 00:04:31,240
It distorts our
understanding of history,

103
00:04:31,240 --> 00:04:33,520
in part because the
meaning of the West

104
00:04:33,520 --> 00:04:35,960
is so wildly
indeterminate, first

105
00:04:35,960 --> 00:04:38,260
drawing a contrast
with the Islamic world,

106
00:04:38,260 --> 00:04:39,980
later with the Orient.

107
00:04:39,980 --> 00:04:41,920
And then in the
Cold War, contrast

108
00:04:41,920 --> 00:04:43,740
with the other side
of the Iron Curtain,

109
00:04:43,740 --> 00:04:46,160
more recently, part of a
more complicated contrast

110
00:04:46,160 --> 00:04:48,200
with the Global South.

111
00:04:48,200 --> 00:04:52,000
If we go back to the root,
Christianity versus Islam,

112
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:56,380
we find religious conflict,
but intellectual common ground.

113
00:04:56,380 --> 00:04:59,900
So the fathers of Western
philosophy, Plato and Aristotle,

114
00:04:59,900 --> 00:05:03,280
had their works preserved by
scholars in the Arab world.

115
00:05:03,280 --> 00:05:08,060
And Muslim, Jewish and Christian
thinkers, Averroes or Ibn Rushd,

116
00:05:08,060 --> 00:05:12,760
Maimonides, Aquinas, all did
the same thing of synthesizing

117
00:05:12,760 --> 00:05:16,160
Aristotle with their different
monotheisms in the 12th and 13th

118
00:05:16,160 --> 00:05:16,700
centuries.

119
00:05:16,700 --> 00:05:19,320
They were all humming
the same tune.

120
00:05:19,320 --> 00:05:22,640
The idea of the West as a
distinctive heritage seems to be

121
00:05:22,640 --> 00:05:24,660
an invention of the 1890s.

122
00:05:24,660 --> 00:05:27,080
And then it gets transformed
through the Cold War.

123
00:05:27,080 --> 00:05:29,480
But actual
intellectual continuity

124
00:05:29,480 --> 00:05:33,300
with Aquinas, let alone
Plato, is very minimal,

125
00:05:33,300 --> 00:05:36,660
as slogans about liberalism
and democracy attest.

126
00:05:36,660 --> 00:05:41,280
Neither Plato nor Aquinas
was a fan of either.

127
00:05:41,280 --> 00:05:43,040
What about the university?

128
00:05:43,040 --> 00:05:47,320
Did woke academics undermine the
Western canon, the Great Books

129
00:05:47,320 --> 00:05:50,280
course, and with it
their own enrollments?

130
00:05:50,280 --> 00:05:51,680
Not really.

131
00:05:51,680 --> 00:05:53,500
It's true that the
canon was, I think,

132
00:05:53,500 --> 00:05:57,590
rightly questioned and
expanded by academics.

133
00:05:57,590 --> 00:05:59,990
I mean, insofar as
inclusion in the canon

134
00:05:59,990 --> 00:06:03,790
is a function of influence,
it tracks social and political

135
00:06:03,790 --> 00:06:05,630
power and the
injustice with which

136
00:06:05,630 --> 00:06:07,790
that power has been exercised.

137
00:06:07,790 --> 00:06:10,590
But courses like Erskine's
and Adler's were still

138
00:06:10,590 --> 00:06:13,590
being offered, if
somewhat revised

139
00:06:13,590 --> 00:06:15,470
and less commonly required.

140
00:06:15,470 --> 00:06:18,870
And humanities enrollments
actually peaked in the 1990s.

141
00:06:18,870 --> 00:06:22,710
So whatever was going on,
students were not put off by it.

142
00:06:22,710 --> 00:06:25,230
Enrollments fell and
continued to fall,

143
00:06:25,230 --> 00:06:29,070
not because of woke, but due to
external pressures, the soaring

144
00:06:29,070 --> 00:06:32,070
cost of higher education,
increasing competition

145
00:06:32,070 --> 00:06:36,070
for desirable jobs, the
mistaken sense that humanities

146
00:06:36,070 --> 00:06:39,470
graduates are not employable,
and a consequent push

147
00:06:39,470 --> 00:06:42,390
to tailor education more
directly to the needs of labor

148
00:06:42,390 --> 00:06:44,270
markets.

149
00:06:44,270 --> 00:06:46,430
MIT is in a special
position with respect

150
00:06:46,430 --> 00:06:48,210
to this in many ways.

151
00:06:48,210 --> 00:06:49,670
One is that the
issue of enrollment

152
00:06:49,670 --> 00:06:53,470
is less relevant because the
supply of students in house

153
00:06:53,470 --> 00:06:54,810
subjects is relatively fixed.

154
00:06:54,810 --> 00:06:58,070
There was no bubble at MIT.

155
00:06:58,070 --> 00:07:01,790
So if the conservative
narrative doesn't hold up,

156
00:07:01,790 --> 00:07:04,870
what reason do we have to
revitalize the Great Books

157
00:07:04,870 --> 00:07:06,030
course?

158
00:07:06,030 --> 00:07:07,470
The short answer
is because there

159
00:07:07,470 --> 00:07:09,990
is an urgent need for
students to grapple

160
00:07:09,990 --> 00:07:14,750
with expansive questions about
human nature, human knowledge,

161
00:07:14,750 --> 00:07:17,630
ethics, society, and politics.

162
00:07:17,630 --> 00:07:20,130
When change is rapid
and unpredictable,

163
00:07:20,130 --> 00:07:23,070
like the unfolding climate
crisis and the socially

164
00:07:23,070 --> 00:07:28,550
disruptive impact of AI, we need
the wider horizons, imagination,

165
00:07:28,550 --> 00:07:31,870
and creative insight
fostered by close engagement

166
00:07:31,870 --> 00:07:34,390
with great books more than ever.

167
00:07:34,390 --> 00:07:36,910
Now we know from
enrollment numbers

168
00:07:36,910 --> 00:07:39,950
that when we're able to offer
classics of Western philosophy

169
00:07:39,950 --> 00:07:42,410
consistently, students
want to take it.

170
00:07:42,410 --> 00:07:45,910
The class size has doubled
over the last three years.

171
00:07:45,910 --> 00:07:48,290
So we're not proposing
new requirements.

172
00:07:48,290 --> 00:07:50,470
We're proposing
courses that we believe

173
00:07:50,470 --> 00:07:53,870
students are excited to take.

174
00:07:53,870 --> 00:07:56,410
Our focus on Western
philosophy, which I think,

175
00:07:56,410 --> 00:07:59,470
unlike Western civilization,
does name something

176
00:07:59,470 --> 00:08:02,230
blurrily coherent,
if rather porous,

177
00:08:02,230 --> 00:08:04,790
is a concession to what
we're best equipped to teach.

178
00:08:04,790 --> 00:08:06,310
That goes along
with self-awareness

179
00:08:06,310 --> 00:08:09,030
about the limits of that
tradition and acknowledgment

180
00:08:09,030 --> 00:08:10,970
of its indebtedness to others.

181
00:08:10,970 --> 00:08:12,950
But given sufficient
resources, there's

182
00:08:12,950 --> 00:08:15,470
a world in which SHASS could
offer a range of subjects

183
00:08:15,470 --> 00:08:20,230
across geographic and cultural
borders that would introduce

184
00:08:20,230 --> 00:08:22,910
students to far-reaching
questions about humanity

185
00:08:22,910 --> 00:08:25,470
through other texts
and traditions flagged

186
00:08:25,470 --> 00:08:28,510
as Great Books courses.

187
00:08:28,510 --> 00:08:30,950
What exactly is the value
for students of spending

188
00:08:30,950 --> 00:08:32,630
time with these books?

189
00:08:32,630 --> 00:08:38,789
It's not to absorb a fixed
body of established wisdom.

190
00:08:38,789 --> 00:08:41,190
It's to learn to
think for themselves

191
00:08:41,190 --> 00:08:43,350
with the help of
living documents that

192
00:08:43,350 --> 00:08:47,630
give historical perspective
and repay close study.

193
00:08:47,630 --> 00:08:51,350
We sometimes argue for the
Humanities and Social Sciences

194
00:08:51,350 --> 00:08:54,030
at MIT as sources of
knowledge and understanding,

195
00:08:54,030 --> 00:08:57,950
of culture and history, society
and social change, ethics

196
00:08:57,950 --> 00:09:00,590
and politics that will
make students better

197
00:09:00,590 --> 00:09:03,190
people and better citizens.

198
00:09:03,190 --> 00:09:05,550
We're not just
preparing MIT students

199
00:09:05,550 --> 00:09:09,410
to land high-paying jobs,
but to solve human problems,

200
00:09:09,410 --> 00:09:12,110
and so to make the
world a better place.

201
00:09:12,110 --> 00:09:14,010
SHASS contributes to this.

202
00:09:14,010 --> 00:09:18,430
And great books courses
can play an important role.

203
00:09:18,430 --> 00:09:20,510
But if all we're
doing is creating

204
00:09:20,510 --> 00:09:22,730
well-intentioned
problem solvers,

205
00:09:22,730 --> 00:09:24,590
we're missing something vital.

206
00:09:24,590 --> 00:09:27,150
I'm reminded of a quip
that was attributed

207
00:09:27,150 --> 00:09:29,790
to the poet WH
Auden, who put words

208
00:09:29,790 --> 00:09:32,150
in the mouth of a social worker.

209
00:09:32,150 --> 00:09:35,910
Quote, "We are all here
on Earth to help others.

210
00:09:35,910 --> 00:09:39,870
What on Earth the others
are here for, I don't know."

211
00:09:39,870 --> 00:09:43,170
If the best we can hope
for is to solve problems,

212
00:09:43,170 --> 00:09:47,830
we'd be better off not having to
face, why bother to live at all?

213
00:09:47,830 --> 00:09:50,350
In the original
meaning, liberal arts

214
00:09:50,350 --> 00:09:52,830
were understood in
opposition to servile arts

215
00:09:52,830 --> 00:09:54,410
or vocational skills.

216
00:09:54,410 --> 00:09:57,550
Liberal education was
fit for a free individual

217
00:09:57,550 --> 00:10:00,610
working out their own
conception of how to live,

218
00:10:00,610 --> 00:10:03,110
including the positive
goods that make life worth

219
00:10:03,110 --> 00:10:04,950
living in the first place.

220
00:10:04,950 --> 00:10:06,570
Art, music, and literature.

221
00:10:06,570 --> 00:10:07,730
Love and friendship.

222
00:10:07,730 --> 00:10:11,390
The beauty of scientific and
mathematical understanding.

223
00:10:11,390 --> 00:10:14,250
Reading profound works of
literature and philosophy,

224
00:10:14,250 --> 00:10:18,190
history and anthropology
can help us to do this.

225
00:10:18,190 --> 00:10:20,230
Of course you could
still ask whether we

226
00:10:20,230 --> 00:10:24,830
need to examine our own lives in
order to live fulfilling ones.

227
00:10:24,830 --> 00:10:28,350
Maybe the unexamined
life can be worth living.

228
00:10:28,350 --> 00:10:30,450
But unless you've
examined that question,

229
00:10:30,450 --> 00:10:32,950
as you would in classics
of Western philosophy,

230
00:10:32,950 --> 00:10:35,470
I'm afraid you're in
no position to say.

231
00:10:35,470 --> 00:10:36,530
Thank you very much.

232
00:10:36,530 --> 00:10:39,995
[APPLAUSE]

233
00:10:39,995 --> 00:10:43,990

234
00:10:43,990 --> 00:10:46,410
I'd like to introduce
Lily Tsai to the stage.

235
00:10:46,410 --> 00:10:49,833
[APPLAUSE]

236
00:10:49,833 --> 00:11:06,470

237
00:11:06,470 --> 00:11:10,150
Sometimes the world can
feel a little crazy.

238
00:11:10,150 --> 00:11:15,230
That's because things are
changing fast, really fast.

239
00:11:15,230 --> 00:11:17,630
It turns out, though,
that what we need to do

240
00:11:17,630 --> 00:11:24,190
is not to move fast with it, but
to stop and reflect and think.

241
00:11:24,190 --> 00:11:26,070
What kind of world
do we really want

242
00:11:26,070 --> 00:11:27,910
to build so that
we're not constantly

243
00:11:27,910 --> 00:11:34,110
overwhelmed by complexity
and chaos and noise?

244
00:11:34,110 --> 00:11:36,270
MIT was originally
built to support

245
00:11:36,270 --> 00:11:38,310
an industrial society,
one that was based

246
00:11:38,310 --> 00:11:41,270
on machines and manufacturing.

247
00:11:41,270 --> 00:11:45,870
Now we're transforming ourselves
for a digital age, one with AI

248
00:11:45,870 --> 00:11:48,450
and computing and
synthetic biology.

249
00:11:48,450 --> 00:11:51,620
And all of these things are
just making change faster.

250
00:11:51,620 --> 00:11:54,270

251
00:11:54,270 --> 00:11:59,270
More than ever, we need to
have moral, intellectual,

252
00:11:59,270 --> 00:12:02,030
and aesthetic judgment.

253
00:12:02,030 --> 00:12:05,390
These are the things
that AI cannot replace.

254
00:12:05,390 --> 00:12:06,370
Don't get me wrong.

255
00:12:06,370 --> 00:12:10,150
Some of my own research is on
designing AI for democracy.

256
00:12:10,150 --> 00:12:14,150
But AI can't tell us if
something is beautiful.

257
00:12:14,150 --> 00:12:17,350
It can't tell us
what a good idea is.

258
00:12:17,350 --> 00:12:23,670
And it definitely can't tell us
what is right and what is wrong.

259
00:12:23,670 --> 00:12:25,370
But if we're not
paying attention,

260
00:12:25,370 --> 00:12:28,750
we're going to fall into
believing that AI can substitute

261
00:12:28,750 --> 00:12:30,270
for these judgments.

262
00:12:30,270 --> 00:12:32,630
So we need to
prepare our students

263
00:12:32,630 --> 00:12:37,590
to reason for themselves
about hard human questions

264
00:12:37,590 --> 00:12:40,790
so they can work together
to build the social fabric

265
00:12:40,790 --> 00:12:46,150
and civic infrastructure
that we need for the future.

266
00:12:46,150 --> 00:12:50,990
Compass teaches students to
build for the common good based

267
00:12:50,990 --> 00:12:55,910
on clear principles and values,
investigated with rigorous tools

268
00:12:55,910 --> 00:12:58,760
from the humanities,
arts, and social sciences.

269
00:12:58,760 --> 00:13:02,375

270
00:13:02,375 --> 00:13:04,750
The first thing that we've
done in the Compass Initiative

271
00:13:04,750 --> 00:13:08,590
is to design a class with the
input of 31 faculty and 30

272
00:13:08,590 --> 00:13:11,910
students from 22 departments.

273
00:13:11,910 --> 00:13:14,450
It's truly a team effort.

274
00:13:14,450 --> 00:13:17,950
And many people, including
Kieran, who I think

275
00:13:17,950 --> 00:13:20,710
joined for our very first
organizational meeting,

276
00:13:20,710 --> 00:13:22,230
and Susan Silbey.

277
00:13:22,230 --> 00:13:26,550
And I'll call out also
Rebecca Sachs and especially

278
00:13:26,550 --> 00:13:30,870
Emily Richmond Pollock, Adam
Albright, and Lila Friedland.

279
00:13:30,870 --> 00:13:37,390
But it's truly a team
effort across the institute.

280
00:13:37,390 --> 00:13:40,030
And it wouldn't be possible
without all of these people

281
00:13:40,030 --> 00:13:44,510
to have all of Compass's
multiple facets.

282
00:13:44,510 --> 00:13:49,390
Compass gets students to grapple
with hard human questions

283
00:13:49,390 --> 00:13:54,310
and to read what great thinkers
have said about these questions.

284
00:13:54,310 --> 00:13:57,950
It teaches students to
debate not in order to win,

285
00:13:57,950 --> 00:14:02,870
but in order to
listen and understand.

286
00:14:02,870 --> 00:14:06,350
Most importantly, we teach
students to apply all of this

287
00:14:06,350 --> 00:14:10,670
to the rapidly changing
world around us.

288
00:14:10,670 --> 00:14:11,950
Here's an example.

289
00:14:11,950 --> 00:14:15,950
We start in the first
week by reflecting on what

290
00:14:15,950 --> 00:14:18,030
holds communities together.

291
00:14:18,030 --> 00:14:21,670
We read the US Constitution
and the Mayflower Compact

292
00:14:21,670 --> 00:14:24,990
and the MIT value statement.

293
00:14:24,990 --> 00:14:28,470
Then we discuss how great
philosophers like Thomas Hobbes

294
00:14:28,470 --> 00:14:31,030
and John Locke and
Jean-Jacques Rousseau

295
00:14:31,030 --> 00:14:32,470
have answered the
question of how

296
00:14:32,470 --> 00:14:35,510
we can have liberty
and individual freedom,

297
00:14:35,510 --> 00:14:38,350
yet still be constrained
to obey the laws

298
00:14:38,350 --> 00:14:41,510
and rules of our communities.

299
00:14:41,510 --> 00:14:43,870
After this, we get
students to apply

300
00:14:43,870 --> 00:14:46,830
what they've learned by
collaborating to write a class

301
00:14:46,830 --> 00:14:48,230
compact together.

302
00:14:48,230 --> 00:14:50,510
You can see a copy of one
of these with the students'

303
00:14:50,510 --> 00:14:53,310
signatures on the bottom.

304
00:14:53,310 --> 00:14:56,170
So each week follows
this basic pattern.

305
00:14:56,170 --> 00:14:58,510
Students read great thinkers.

306
00:14:58,510 --> 00:15:01,430
They debate and deliberate
on a fundamental question

307
00:15:01,430 --> 00:15:03,150
about human existence.

308
00:15:03,150 --> 00:15:07,070
And then they apply it
to a real world problem.

309
00:15:07,070 --> 00:15:09,670
We're hopefully
remaking a liberal arts

310
00:15:09,670 --> 00:15:11,050
for the digital age.

311
00:15:11,050 --> 00:15:14,470
But that's a talk
for another day.

312
00:15:14,470 --> 00:15:18,230
In Compass, we investigate
three big questions.

313
00:15:18,230 --> 00:15:21,190
And we keep coming back to them.

314
00:15:21,190 --> 00:15:23,220
What do we value, and why?

315
00:15:23,220 --> 00:15:25,790

316
00:15:25,790 --> 00:15:27,190
What do we know?

317
00:15:27,190 --> 00:15:30,270
And how do we know it?

318
00:15:30,270 --> 00:15:32,530
And what do we
owe to each other?

319
00:15:32,530 --> 00:15:37,350
What is the kind of world that
we want to build together?

320
00:15:37,350 --> 00:15:40,070
After discussing John
Stuart Mill and Immanuel

321
00:15:40,070 --> 00:15:43,990
Kant, virtue ethicists like
Aristotle and Confucius,

322
00:15:43,990 --> 00:15:46,150
we map our personal values.

323
00:15:46,150 --> 00:15:48,790
And we figure out whether or
not our professional values

324
00:15:48,790 --> 00:15:51,630
in our fields reflect that.

325
00:15:51,630 --> 00:15:53,670
We read Dante and Shakespeare.

326
00:15:53,670 --> 00:15:57,150
This semester, we took students
to Verdi's Macbeth opera

327
00:15:57,150 --> 00:15:59,470
and Beethoven's
Seventh Symphony.

328
00:15:59,470 --> 00:16:02,070
And we asked them to
reflect on the value

329
00:16:02,070 --> 00:16:08,830
of aesthetic and artistic
experience and expression.

330
00:16:08,830 --> 00:16:11,750
By the end of the
semester, Compass students

331
00:16:11,750 --> 00:16:13,870
have started to
surface the structure

332
00:16:13,870 --> 00:16:19,310
and principles of history,
politics, science, poetry,

333
00:16:19,310 --> 00:16:19,860
and music.

334
00:16:19,860 --> 00:16:22,750

335
00:16:22,750 --> 00:16:27,270
This focus on reasoning about
hard human questions using

336
00:16:27,270 --> 00:16:31,090
rigorous tools from the many
disciplines in the humanities,

337
00:16:31,090 --> 00:16:34,670
arts, and social
sciences is the essence

338
00:16:34,670 --> 00:16:37,990
of Compass's unique approach.

339
00:16:37,990 --> 00:16:40,350
Let me show you what I mean.

340
00:16:40,350 --> 00:16:44,500
True or false, MIT
is a meritocracy.

341
00:16:44,500 --> 00:16:47,920
If you ask a room full of
MIT students this question,

342
00:16:47,920 --> 00:16:52,060
many, probably even
most of them, say true.

343
00:16:52,060 --> 00:16:53,340
But why?

344
00:16:53,340 --> 00:16:56,900
What does it mean
to be a meritocracy?

345
00:16:56,900 --> 00:16:58,740
What is merit, even?

346
00:16:58,740 --> 00:17:01,020
Is mathematical ability merit?

347
00:17:01,020 --> 00:17:03,940
Is hard work merit?

348
00:17:03,940 --> 00:17:06,740
And how would one
value these things

349
00:17:06,740 --> 00:17:10,099
in the context of a university?

350
00:17:10,099 --> 00:17:12,680
And how do we know
someone's merit?

351
00:17:12,680 --> 00:17:15,420
Do we measure it with
problem sets and tests?

352
00:17:15,420 --> 00:17:18,500
Or do we figure it
out some other way?

353
00:17:18,500 --> 00:17:21,420
And once we know what
we value as merit

354
00:17:21,420 --> 00:17:25,140
and how we know something
is meritorious, what

355
00:17:25,140 --> 00:17:29,740
do we owe to those who have
merit in this context and those

356
00:17:29,740 --> 00:17:32,340
who do not?

357
00:17:32,340 --> 00:17:35,980
So you can see how a simple,
knee jerk, true-false response

358
00:17:35,980 --> 00:17:41,500
quickly unspools into a long
string of difficult questions.

359
00:17:41,500 --> 00:17:44,900
These kinds of questions need
the different disciplines

360
00:17:44,900 --> 00:17:48,240
of philosophy, political
science, anthropology,

361
00:17:48,240 --> 00:17:51,660
and history in order to
know how to reason about how

362
00:17:51,660 --> 00:17:54,700
we should answer them.

363
00:17:54,700 --> 00:17:56,620
You might ask,
why does it matter

364
00:17:56,620 --> 00:18:01,260
if we can reason more rigorously
about these kinds of questions?

365
00:18:01,260 --> 00:18:04,820
Well, one, it helps us
diagnose disagreements.

366
00:18:04,820 --> 00:18:07,180
If two people disagree
about whether or not

367
00:18:07,180 --> 00:18:10,820
MIT is a meritocracy, is
it because they disagree

368
00:18:10,820 --> 00:18:13,620
about the values or
because they don't agree

369
00:18:13,620 --> 00:18:16,060
about the facts on the ground?

370
00:18:16,060 --> 00:18:17,780
Breaking down the
question allows

371
00:18:17,780 --> 00:18:20,660
us to figure out the
points of agreement,

372
00:18:20,660 --> 00:18:23,860
and maybe uncertainty,
and to be clear about what

373
00:18:23,860 --> 00:18:26,860
we do disagree about.

374
00:18:26,860 --> 00:18:30,980
Two, it invites us to be more
reflective and intentional

375
00:18:30,980 --> 00:18:32,980
about our own beliefs.

376
00:18:32,980 --> 00:18:35,780
If we think math
skills are meritorious,

377
00:18:35,780 --> 00:18:37,740
are there other kinds
of merit that we

378
00:18:37,740 --> 00:18:42,700
should prioritize just as
much based on the same logic?

379
00:18:42,700 --> 00:18:45,940
Finally, it helps
us take action.

380
00:18:45,940 --> 00:18:48,140
If we're in a position of power.

381
00:18:48,140 --> 00:18:51,460
What kinds of decisions
would accomplish

382
00:18:51,460 --> 00:18:52,830
the rewarding of merit?

383
00:18:52,830 --> 00:18:55,460

384
00:18:55,460 --> 00:18:59,220
MIT students need to be fluent
in reasoning about answers

385
00:18:59,220 --> 00:19:02,580
to these hard human questions.

386
00:19:02,580 --> 00:19:04,200
Some of them will
become engineers.

387
00:19:04,200 --> 00:19:06,300
And they'll need to know
the values and impacts

388
00:19:06,300 --> 00:19:08,780
of the systems they design.

389
00:19:08,780 --> 00:19:11,320
Some will become
parents or educators.

390
00:19:11,320 --> 00:19:15,660
And they'll need to know
what to reward and why.

391
00:19:15,660 --> 00:19:18,000
Many of them will
become leaders.

392
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:20,420
And they'll have to make
policies and decisions that

393
00:19:20,420 --> 00:19:24,580
influence institutional
and societal structures.

394
00:19:24,580 --> 00:19:27,540
And all, we hope, will
face disagreements

395
00:19:27,540 --> 00:19:31,580
about hard questions
with respect and humility

396
00:19:31,580 --> 00:19:34,200
and tools for
understanding differences.

397
00:19:34,200 --> 00:19:36,860

398
00:19:36,860 --> 00:19:38,780
The multidisciplinarity
of Compass

399
00:19:38,780 --> 00:19:42,620
gives people all the puzzle
pieces together at one table

400
00:19:42,620 --> 00:19:46,380
to understand, what are the
multisystemic challenges

401
00:19:46,380 --> 00:19:48,860
of the digital era?

402
00:19:48,860 --> 00:19:51,380
I don't know of any
other place where

403
00:19:51,380 --> 00:19:55,940
an approach this deep
and complex is happening.

404
00:19:55,940 --> 00:19:58,760
Even though we've just
